The life cycle of Chinchero is brought full circle inChapter 7, Llacta/Community, and in the Epilogue thatfollows.Anoverviewofthechangesthatoccurredatthesite afterTopaIncas death tellsarobust taleofbetrayaland political maneuverings that quickly led to a familysplit, a difficult succession in rulers, and the imprisonmentofasonatChinchero.Asinmanycasesthroughoutthe New World, Spanish occupation of the estate led torepurposing of its buildings and open spaces and toneglectofothers.AnewlyimposedviceregaltownplanpermanentlyalteredthedesignandconfigurationofTopaIncas estate. The chapter speaks to the resilience andtenacity of its indigenous inhabitants over time and thefuture challenges they face.
AtHomewiththeSapaInca addstoagrowingbodyof research on the Inca and their royal estates. Its theoreticalapproachandrichcontentwillappealtoanumberofdisciplinaryinterests,anditsmethodswillhaveapplications beyond any one site or geographic area. Thisengaging, meticulously researched, and clearly writtenmonograph is well suited for course adaptation. Itpromises to become one of the classic studies of theInca and their magnificent architectural legacy, and toserve as puncu, an opening from which future studieswill follow. 
Political Strategies in PreColumbian Mesoamerica. SARAH KURNICK and JOANNE BARON, editors.2016.UniversityPressofColorado,Boulder.xv+291pp.36 illus. $60(hardcover), ISBN 9781607324157. 
Reviewed by Nancy Gonlin, Bellevue College 
ThiseditedvolumebySarahKurnickandJoanneBaronaptlyhighlightscurrenttrendsinthestudyofarchaeopolitics in Mesoamerica. The book contains eight chaptersthat cover the Maya (Formative, Classic, Postclassic),theTerminalFormativeincoastalOaxaca,EarlyClassicCentralJalisco,ClassicTeotihuacan,thePostclassicMixtec,andtheTarascansinMichoacn,aswellasanexcellent summary chapter. The chapters are based on asymposium that covered a greater geographical andchronologicalspanthanpresentedhere.Twomajorissuesaddressed by each chapter are how those exercisingauthority compel others to obey and why individualschoose to recognize, or reject, such authority (p. 24).Theroleofritualisundeniableandisfeaturedextensively 
as politics and religion are intertwined. The concept ofcontradictionisfoundthroughoutthevolumeandisusedto frame discussions about political authority inMesoamerica. 
The stated themes clearly run through the chaptersandtheeditorshavedoneaworthyjoboftyingtogethervarioustimes,places,andcultures.SarahKurnicksintroductorychapterreviewsthepertinentliteratureontermswe commonly use to discuss politics (e.g., authority,agency,legitimacy,power, etc.).Thedialectical of rulerandrulediscentraltoeachchapter.OnethingthatIparticularly like about this collection is that each authorincorporates the role of commoners (followers, nonelites, etc.) in the equation of power and authority.
Takeshi Inomata (Chapter 2) questions whether useof the modern political is applicable to archaeologicalcontextsanddeconstructstermswetakeforgranted.Thecase study of Formative Ceibal is used to illustrate thisphilosophical discourse but needs more supportingdetails about the archaeology to better evaluate the theoreticalconstructs.Theeditingofreferencesinthisparticularchapterwentastray,withdoubleentriesforsomeitems and others out of order. 
ArthurA.Joyce,SarahB.Barber,JeffreyBrzezinski,Carlo J. Lucido, andVictor Salazar Chvez (Chapter 3)contributeastimulatingchapterwithabundantevidenceof the fledgling complex society along the RoVerde incoastal Oaxaca. Deftly illustrated is the point that monumental architecturedoes notequalpoliticalstabilityinthis dynamic society centered at RoViejo.The authorsdo not dwell as much on the usage of terms (authority,power) as others in this volume, but usefully employthemtoarriveatanunderstandingofthisLateFormativecomplex society.
Consideration of the role of conflict, ritual, and lineages in the quest for political domination is illustratedintheTequilaValleysofWesternMexico,whereChristopher S. Beekman (Chapter 4) has investigated theremains of guachimontones (circular temples), ballcourts,residential areas,andshafttombsthat were builtduring the Late Formative/Early Classic by people ofthe Teuchitln polity.The use of ethnographic informationonthecontemporaryNyariisnotsomuchfordirectanalogyasitisforinterpretingpossibilitiesinthearchaeologicalrecord.Beekmansuccinctlycharacterizesongoing political dynamics by summarizing that conflictsdonotneedtoberesolved,butneitheraretheyleftunaddressed (p. 113).
Joanne Baron (Chapter 5) uses middlerange theorytoeffectivelyconnectcurrentpracticeswithancientonesin the Maya area. The evaluation of the role of patrondeityworshipandancestorvenerationrestsuponexceptionallywelldocumentedarchaeologicalandepigraphicremainsatLaCorona,Guatemala.Someofthebestevidence for feasting has been documented at La Corona. 

